            <th class="py-2 pr-4">Math</th>
            <th class="py-2 pr-4">Scheme</th>
            <th class="py-2 pr-4">Python</th>
            <th class="py-2">Meaning</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="font-mono">
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-4">w, b</td><td class="pr-4 text-green-300">w, b</td><td class="pr-4 text-blue-300">w, b</td><td class="font-sans">Weight and bias</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-4">X&#x1D40;X</td><td class="pr-4 text-green-300">(dot xc xc)</td><td class="pr-4 text-blue-300">sum(x*x for x in xc)</td><td class="font-sans">Inner product</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-4">&nabla;L</td><td class="pr-4 text-green-300">dw, db</td><td class="pr-4 text-blue-300">dw, db</td><td class="font-sans">Gradient of loss</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-4">&eta;</td><td class="pr-4 text-green-300">lr</td><td class="pr-4 text-blue-300">lr</td><td class="font-sans">Learning rate</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="py-2 pr-4">MSE</td><td class="pr-4 text-green-300">(mse preds ys)</td><td class="pr-4 text-blue-300">mse</td><td class="font-sans">Mean squared error</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <!-- Translation notes -->
    <h3>Translation notes</h3>
    <p>The normal equation computes the answer in one pass &mdash; clean and functional. Gradient descent is inherently iterative: each step depends on the previous weights. Scheme handles this via tail recursion (<code>train</code> calls itself with updated <code>w</code> and <code>b</code>). Python uses a <code>for</code> loop with mutation. Same computation, different idioms.</p>
    <p class="mt-2">In practice, gradient descent wins for large datasets because the normal equation requires inverting X&#x1D40;X, which is O(d&#xB3;) in the number of features. Gradient descent is O(nd) per step.</p>

